metadata.title: Examining the fields in a crash report

inlineContent.text: Each section of a crash report contains information to help you diagnose the source
of a crash.
A crash report begins with a header section that describes the environment the crash
occurred in.
The fields in the header can contain the following information. No single crash report
contains all of these fields.
: A unique identifier for the report. Two reports never share
the same
: An anonymized per-device identifier. Two reports from the
same device contain identical values. This identifier is reset upon erasing the device.
: A unique identifier for the combination of the device and vendor
of the crashed application. Two reports for apps from the same vendor and from the
same device contain identical values. This field is only present for TestFlight builds
of an app, and replaces the
field.
: The specific device model the app was running on.
: The executable name for the process that crashed. This matches the
value in the app’s information property list. The number in brackets is the process
ID.
: The location of the executable on disk. macOS replaces user-identifable
path components with placeholder values to protect privacy.

of the process that crashed. If the binary doesn’t have a
this field contains either the process name or a placeholder value.
: The version of the process that crashed. The value is a concatenation
of the app’s

thin your app to device specific variants.
: The specific variant of your app produced by app thinning. This field
contains multiple values, described later in this section.

assigned to the process at the time of termination. This field is generally not helpful
when you analyze a crash report.
: The name and process ID (in square brackets) of the process that
launched the crashed process.
: The name of the process coalition containing the app. Process coalitions
track resource usage among groups of related processes, such as an operating system
process supporting a specific API’s functionality in an app. Most processes, including
app extensions, form their own coalition.
: The date and time of the crash.
: The date and time the app launched.
: The operating system version, including the build number, on which
the crash occurred.

Every crash report contains exception information. This information section tells
you how the process terminated, but it may not fully explain why the app terminated.
This information is important, but is often overlooked.
This exception information doesn’t refer to language exceptions thrown by
an API or language features in Objective-C or C++. Crash reports record language
exception information separately.
The following fields provide information about the exception. No single crash report
contains all of these fields.
: The name of the Mach exception that terminated the process, along
with the name of the corresponding BSD termination signal in parentheses. See
: Processor specific information about the exception encoded into
one or more 64-bit hexadecimal numbers. Typically, this field isn’t present because
the operating system presents the information as human-readable information in the
other fields of this section.
: The human-readable description of the exception codes.
: Additional human-readable information extracted from the exception
codes.
: Additional information that isn’t specific to one exception type.
If this field contains
, the crash didn’t originate from a hardware
trap, either because the process was explicitly terminated by the operating system
or the process called

, the process didn’t crash, but the operating system might have subsequently

inlineContent.code: NON-FATAL CONDITION (this is NOT a crash)

inlineContent.text: , the process didn’t terminate, because the issue that created
the crash report wasn’t fatal.
: Exit reason information specified when the operating system
terminates a process. Key operating system components, both inside and outside of
a process, terminate the process upon encountering a fatal error and record the reason
in this field. Examples of the information you can find in this field are messages
about an invalid code signature, a missing dependent library, or accessing privacy
sensitive information without a purpose string.
or
: The thread on which the exception originated.
The operating system sometimes includes additional diagnostic information. This information
uses a variety of formats, depending on reason for the crash, and isn’t present in
every crash report.
Framework error messages occurring just before the process terminated appear in the
field. In this example, the
framework logged an error about incorrect use of a dispatch queue:

code: BUG IN CLIENT OF LIBDISPATCH: dispatch_sync called on queue already owned by current thread

Terminations due to a memory access issue contain information about the virtual memory
regions in the
field.

code: VM Region Info: 0 is not in any region.  Bytes before following region: 4307009536
REGION TYPE                      START - END             [ VSIZE] PRT/MAX SHRMOD  REGION DETAIL

Each thread of the crashed proces is captured as a backtrace, documenting the code
running on the thread when the process terminated. The backtraces are similar to
what you see when you pause the process with the debugger. Crashes caused by a language
exception include an additional backtrace, the
, located
before the first thread. If your crash report contains a
see
for information specific to language
exception crashes.
The first line of each backtrace lists the thread number and the thread name. For
privacy reasons, crash reports delivered through the
in Xcode don’t contain thread names. This example shows the backtraces for three
threads;
crashed, and is identified as the app’s main thread by its name:
After the thread number, each line of a backtrace represents a stack frame in the
backtrace.
Each column of the stack frame contains information about the code executing at the
time of the crash. The following list uses the components of stack frame 0 from the
example above.
. The stack frame number. Stack frames are in calling order, where frame 0 is
the function that was executing at the time execution halted. Frame 1 is the function
that called the function in frame 0, and so on.
. The name of the binary containing the function that is executing.
. The address of the machine instruction that is executing.
For frame 0 in each backtrace, this is the address of the machine instruction executing
on a thread when the process terminated. For other stack frames, this is the address
of first machine instruction that executes after control returns to that stack frame.
. In a fully symbolicated crash
report, the name of the function that is executing. For privacy reasons, the function
name is sometimes limited to the first 100 characters.
. The number after the
is the byte offset from the function’s entry
point to the current instruction in the function.
. The file name and line number containing the code, if you
have a
file for the binary.
In some situations, the file name or the line number information won’t correspond
to the orginial source code:
If the source file name is
, the compiler created the code
for that frame, and the code isn’t in your source files. If this is top frame in
the crashed thread, look at the preceeding few stack frames for clues.
If the line number for a source file is
, this means the backtrace doesn’t map
to a specific line of code in the original code. This is because the compiler optimized
the code, such as by inlining functions, and the code executing at the time of the
crash doesn’t correspond to an exact line in the orignial code. The function name
for the frame is still a clue in this situation.
The thread state section of a crash report lists the CPU registers and their values
for the crashed thread when the app terminated. Understanding the thread state is
an advanced topic that requires understanding of the application binary interface
(ABI). See

code: Thread 0 crashed with ARM Thread State (64-bit):

discusses that scenario further.
The binary images section of a crash report lists all code loaded in the process
at the time of termination, such as the app executable and system frameworks. Each
line in the Binary Images section represents a single binary image. iOS, iPadOS, tvOS, visionOS, and watchOS use the following format:
This list contains the components from the preceding example:
. The binary image’s address range within the process.
The first address is the binary’s load address. See

into the process.
. A build UUID that uniquely identifies the binary
image. Use this value to locate the corresponding
file when symbolicating
the crash report. See
for
more information on build UUIDs.
. The path to the binary on disk.
macOS replaces user-identifable path components with placeholder values to protect
privacy.
